26. Qg3 $2 {First things first, we should not go backwards with our pieces.
Second. we should play with a plan. Playing with a plan means that we should
create active pieces and then strike. The move queen to g3 doesn't help White
to create active pieces. Here, White should play the forcing move f5, which
could keep him out of trouble. Last, but not least, White should ask: "What is
the threat from Black?" If we take a close look at Black's pieces, then we can
understand that they are active and ready to strike in the center. Black would
first like to play e5 and then d5. White has a tactical problem. This
particular problem has a name - bishop b2 - as it is unprotected. Of course,
it is very difficult to spot the bishop on b2 but it is easy to play forcing
moves like f5. The conclusion is this: always try to play attacking and
forcing moves.} (26. f5 $5 {Playing forcefully...}) (26. Ba1 $5 {Profilaxis})
